Someone came to fix my kitchen floor, so I'm going to pretend I still have a job and work from home while reviewing Too Hot to Handle.
If I can only open this damned file. (Damn OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm in.
And that's where he starts drilling really hard. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of turning my air purifier all the way up makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like wood shavings, so it's justified even though it's an anti-mask. Plus, I really need to protect myself, right??
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he leaves.
The good news is that I've finished rereading chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but there's a lot of suspense. Good work.
Doing find-and-replace on … ➡️ ellipsis character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But anyway, I stick to it. The most natural speeches are usually choppy, especially when people let their emotions take over.
The craftsman is vacuuming, and with a bit of luck, he will soon be done.
He went out (as far as I can hear) to cut something. So I took a look to see how he was progressing. It's far from done :(
Only 7 pages left on chapter five. It remains my favorite chapter, and it's quite substantial. Some layout changes, and minor adjustments to switch to active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I would really like a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still tinkering in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The craftsman is gone!
He told me he had gotten a quote for the entire floor, but the owners were cheap and only paid for the small damaged area near the door. It's clearly better.
The house is ventilating, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
